Data Analysis Based on Video game sales data¶

In this tutorial, We will investigate the video game sales data, tidy it and provide some valuable insights. This data comes from Kaggle.com and contains more than 16000 games. With all these information, we may observe something interesting.

Data Collection¶

In the first stage, we choose 3 datasets to start the project. Both datasets are downloaded from www.Kaggle.com. They are relatively clear to analysize and visualize. Since we both interested in video game, we choose our primary Video Game Sales data and Google Play Store Apps as the backup plan.

We use Video Game Sales as primary dataset since it is our common interest. This dataset contains detailed sales data in different place. The second dataset we interested in is Google Play Store Apps. This dataset provides information of 9660 unique apps on Android platform. Some of them are very polular and high-rated. A complimentary dataset would be Apple iOS app store statistics, we can also compare the performance of the same app on different platforms.

The third dataset is GDP data which contains GDP in different areas from 1960 to 2018. It is very possible that game sales is related to the overall economy.

dataset 1: Video game sales¶

we get this dataset from https://www.kaggle.com/gregorut/videogamesales

The video game sales dataset contains 16,598 games with sales greater than 100,000 copies, generated by a scrape of vgchartz.com . It has 11 attributes including:

Columns of video game sales:¶

  • Rank-ranking of overall sales
  • Name-the video game name
  • Platform-platform of the games release(i.e. Wii, Nes, GB, PC, PS4, etc. 31 values)
  • Year-year of the games release
  • Genre-genre of the game(i.e. action, sports, etc. 12 values)
  • Publisher-publisher of the game(i.e. electronic arts, Activision, Nintendo, etc. 579 values)
  • NA_sales-total sales in North America(in million)
  • EU_sales-total sales in Europe(in million)
  • JP_sales-total sales in Japan(in million)
  • Other_sales-total sales in the rest of the world(in million)
  • Global_sales-total worldwide sales

Problems and interest points:¶

  • Is the ranking associates with genre or the platform?
  • What is the trend of genre of popular video games over years? Does it have relationship with the platform? How does it distributed?
  • What is the most popular platform for video games over the years? We can analyze it with the platform publication news.
  • Does different publisher has a trend to publish a specific genre of video games?
  • Compare the sales over different areas, compute the ratio between sales and population, does it have relationship with the development of the area?
  • Does different areas has different favor of genre or platform of the video game? We can analyze it considering the culture and publisher of areas.

We can visualize the above questions with kinds of vivid plots, and tidy the data focusing on each individual question.

dataset 2: Google Play Store Apps¶

we download this data from https://www.kaggle.com/lava18/google-play-store-apps

The Play Store apps data has enormous potential to drive app-making businesses to success. Some insights can be drawn for developers to work on and capture the Android market.

There are 13 columns and 9660 rows in this dataset. Each row contains a unique App from Google Play Store

Attributes of google play store apps:¶

  • App: name of the App
  • Category: type of the App
  • Rating: application's rating on playstore
  • Reviews: number of reviews
  • Size: size of app in M, sometimes varies with device.
  • Installs: number of instrallments
  • Type: whether the app is free or paid
  • Price: price of the App in dollar, if the app is free, price equals to zero
  • Content Rating: everyone, teens, mature 17+ etc. 7 values total
  • Genres: App genres(i.e. tools, education, lifestyle etc. 120 values total)
  • Last Updated: data of latest update
  • Current Ver: latest App version
  • Android Ver: Minimum Android Version required to run the App

Problems:¶

  • Why some apps are high-rated while other not?
  • Is rating related to genres?
  • Is high rating apps always updating?
  • If we are developing a new app on Android, how to get our app high_rated?
  • Given other information, can we predict the rating of an app?

Data Processing: Extraction, Transform, Load and Data Analysis¶

We use video games sales data to finish this part. One complementary data is GDP per capita from 1960 to 2018, which helps us to calculate the correlation coefficient with the sales. The video games dataset is already pretty tidy. But we can see there are around 300 null data in Year and 50 null data in Publisher. We believe it is neither caused by scraping or original web don't have this information (missing at random).

Consider it too exhausted to google each game and fill in the blank we don't have a good way to fill in and none of these data has high rank and the missing number is not that large, we will just use drop null to ignore them.

Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization¶

Ranking over Genre/Platform¶

In this part, we would like to investigate if the ranking is associated with genre or the platform. We only consider the top 500 rank over the table, since we think the rest may not be representative and may affect the result(we also tried the top 100, the results are similar), we used bar plots of the mean rank vs. genre/platform to visualize them. The shorter of the bar, the higher ranking of the genre/platform.

  • From the first plot(mean ranking over genre), platform and racing games have higher ranking, while fighing and adventure games have lower ranking.
  • From the second plot(mean ranking over platform), GB and Wii have higher ranking, XOne PC and PS2 have lower ranking. Accroding to Google, GB is gameboy published by Nintendo in 90s, which is a quite heat during that time. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_Boy

Trends of Genre or Platform over Years¶

In this part, we want to know the trend of genre/platform of popular video games over years. We calculate how many video games published in the each year of each genre and platform. Since there are so many platforms, and lots of them are not well-known, we only plot the top 10 platforms which has the most video games.

  • From the first plot(overall video game over year),there are rarely video games before 1990, the video games market starts to thrive from 1990, the market arrives its peak around 2009, and start to drop off after 2010.
  • From the second plot(trends of genre over years) and third plot(overall video game counts by genre), action and sports games are accounted for a large part, sports video games first thrives around 2002, and action video games catch up around 2006.
  • From the fourth plot(overall video game counts by platform), most video games are published on only few platform, they are not evenly distributed, we can only count for the top 10 platform.
  • From the fifth plot(trends of top10 platform over years) and sixth plot(overall video game counts by top10 platform), PS took over the market over 1995-2000, PS2 GBA XB took over the market over 2000-2005, DS took the majority of th market in 2009, followed by Wii and X360. But PC exists the longest period, it becomes popular since 1985., although it doesn't take much of the market. DS and PS2 published the highest number of video games.
  • From the seventh plot(genre vs. platform heatmap), sports video games are popular in PS2, music video games are popular in DS, and action video games are popular in DS, PS2, etc.

Trends of Area Sales (Percentage) over Years¶

In this part, we ploted the sales percentage of four areas over years to see the trends. It fits the conclusion we got from above sections.

  • the video games market starts to thrive from 1995, the market arrives its peak around 2009, and start to drop off after 2010.
  • NA really takes a large amount in sales market.
  • JP also takes a large amount around 1953-1955 and 2015-now. Since the sales are measured in money, we need to consider the population of each area, Japan apparently has smaller population across the four areas, but it still takes a large part of the markets, which means video games are heated in Japan across the long time.
  • Japan has 126.8 million population, North America has 579 million population, Europe has 741.4 million population according to the 2017 statistics, the video games are really popular in japan, also explains why the Nintendo is considered to be the largest publisher of all the video games market.

Correlation of GDP of Areas¶

In this part, we found a dataset of GDP in NA, EU, JP and world. We grouped the video games dataset by years, and sum the sales for each year, we computed the correlation coefficient of sales and GDP for each area across year and made a bar plot to visualize it.

  • All the correlation coefficients are positive and over 0.6, which makes sense to say the sales is positive correlative with GDP.
  • Europe has the highest corrlation coefficient which is over 0.8, we consider it highly correlated.

years=vgsales_df.groupby("Year").sum()
cross=years.merge(gdp_df,on=['Year'],how="inner")
corr_NA=cross["NA_Sales"].corr(cross["North America"])
corr_EU=cross["EU_Sales"].corr(cross["Euro area"])
corr_JP=cross["JP_Sales"].corr(cross["Japan"])
corr_global=cross["Global_Sales"].corr(cross["World"])
x=['NA','EU','JP','Global']
y=[corr_NA,corr_EU,corr_JP,corr_global]
x_pos=[i for i, _ in enumerate(x)]
plt.bar(x_pos,y)
plt.xlabel("Area")
plt.ylabel("correlation coefficient")
plt.title("correlation coefficient sales with GDP over areas")
plt.xticks(x_pos,x)
plt.show()

Does different publisher has a trend to publish a specific genre of video games?¶

Does different publisher has a trend to publish a specific genre of video games? Our first guess is yes. Based on history and techonology background, different company has different preference. Once a company launched a successful game, it is highly possible for them produce a follow_up and than developed as a preference. Let's first take a look at the publishers of top 100 video games. These games are produced by 11 different publisher. From the last column our first table, we can see Nintendo owns 52 of 100 top games. This is so surprising!

In [25]:
genre = vgsales_df['Genre'].unique()
labels = genre
sns.set(font_scale = 0.8)
for publisher in great_pub:
    markers = np.linspace(0,max(pub_genre[publisher]),num = 11)
    str_markers = [str(x) for x in markers]
    def radar_chart(title, stats, att_labels = labels, plot_markers = markers, plot_str_markers = str_markers):

        labels = np.array(att_labels)

        angles = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, len(labels), endpoint=False)
        stats = np.concatenate((stats,[stats[0]]))
        angles = np.concatenate((angles,[angles[0]]))

        fig= plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
        ax = fig.add_subplot(111, polar=True)
        ax.plot(angles, stats, '.-', linewidth=1)
        ax.fill(angles, stats, alpha=0.25)
        ax.set_thetagrids(angles * 180/np.pi, labels)
        plt.yticks(markers)
        ax.set_title(title)
        ax.grid(True)

        return plt.show()

    radar_chart(publisher, pub_genre[publisher])

From the above radar chart, we can see the top publisher in the industry do have a preference of making different genres of games. Nintendo's kind of a balanced-development company, which is good at puzzle, simulation and role-playing, while Activision extremely loves sports and Take-Two interactive preferred adventure. For most of the 7 publishers, They do have a obvious genre preference.

Prediction of game sales model¶

The last part of our tutorial is to build a model to predict video games sales. We think GDP data can explain part of question, so we first merge these two data set. And then, we build a KNeighborsRegressor model with k being 20, but the result show a large bias. Thus we decide to find the k that can optimize our model. We use top 2000 games to do this regression.

from sklearn.feature_extraction import DictVectorizer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

vg_df = vg_df.dropna(subset = ['Publisher'])

features = ["Platform", "Year", "Genre","World"]

# Define the training data.
# Represent the features as a list of dicts.
X_train_dict = vg_df[features].to_dict(orient="records")
y_train = vg_df["Global_Sales"]

# Dummy encoding
vec = DictVectorizer(sparse=False)
vec.fit(X_train_dict)
X_train = vec.transform(X_train_dict)

# Standardization
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X_train)
X_train_sc = scaler.transform(X_train)


# K-Nearest Neighbors Model
model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=20)
model.fit(X_train_sc, y_train)

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.feature_extraction import DictVectorizer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

vg_df_2000 = vg_df_2000.dropna(subset = ['Publisher'])

features = ["Platform", "Year", "Genre","World"]

# Define the training data.
# Represent the features as a list of dicts.
X_train_dict = vg_df_2000[features].to_dict(orient="records")
y_train = vg_df_2000["Global_Sales"]

# Dummy encoding

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

vec = DictVectorizer(sparse=False)
scaler = StandardScaler()


# calculates estimate of test error based on 10-fold cross validation
def get_cv_error(k):
    model = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k)
    pipeline = Pipeline([("vectorizer", vec), ("scaler", scaler), ("fit", model)])
    mse = np.mean(-cross_val_score(
        pipeline, X_train_dict, y_train, 
        cv=10, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error"
    ))
    return mse
    
ks = pd.Series(range(1, 20))
ks.index = range(1, 20)
test_errs = ks.apply(get_cv_error)

test_errs.plot.line()
test_errs.sort_values()

Insight & Policy Dicision¶

In this tutorial, we tested several hypothesis and they fit in with our common sense.

  • North American takes the largest part of the video games sales market overall.
  • Japan has the largest sales per person in the market, and they really like role-playing game.
  • Nintendo is the largest publisher of the video games market, and they are pretty popular. The Nintendos stock is recommended to preserve, especially they published a new game or a new platform, as long as the video games market is still a heat.
  • To make the prediction of game sales better, we need more data such as game investment and advertising fee.
